\subsection{Model Overview}
\label{sec:model_overview}
We introduce MoST (Mixture of Speech and Text), a unified foundation model designed to seamlessly process and generate both speech and text modalities within a single, end-to-end architecture. MoST builds upon a pre-trained large language model (LLM) featuring a Mixture of Experts (MoE) structure, adapting it for multimodal tasks through several key innovations.
A core distinction of MoST lies in its handling of audio input. Unlike prior approaches that often rely on discretizing audio into tokens (e.g., \cite{audiolm, spiritlm}), MoST processes continuous audio waveforms directly. This is achieved by integrating a dedicated audio encoder, specifically a pre-trained HuBERT model \cite{hsu2021hubert}, followed by a projection layer. Given an input audio waveform \( \mathbf{A} \), the audio encoder \( E_{audio} \) produces a sequence of continuous representations \( \mathbf{H}_{audio} = E_{audio}(\mathbf{A}) \in \mathbb{R}^{L_{audio} \times d_{model}} \), where \( L_{audio} \) is the sequence length of the audio features and \( d_{model} \) is the model's hidden dimension. This approach aims to preserve the rich information inherent in the raw audio signal, mitigating potential information loss associated with quantization or tokenization.
For text input, standard tokenization is employed, followed by an embedding layer \( E_{text} \). Given text tokens \( \mathbf{T} \), the corresponding embeddings are \( \mathbf{H}_{text} = E_{text}(\mathbf{T}) \in \mathbb{R}^{L_{text} \times d_{model}} \). MoST constructs a unified input sequence by interleaving or concatenating \( \mathbf{H}_{audio} \) and \( \mathbf{H}_{text} \) based on the input structure, potentially demarcated by special tokens (as detailed in Section \ref{sec:audio_encoder}). Let the resulting combined input representation be \( \mathbf{H}_{input} \in \mathbb{R}^{L_{input} \times d_{model}} \).
The core of MoST is a transformer decoder, adapted from the base MoE LLM. Crucially, specific layers within this decoder incorporate our proposed Modality-Aware Mixture of Experts (MAMoE) mechanism (detailed in Section \ref{sec:mamoe}). This mechanism dynamically routes tokens based on their modality (speech-derived or text-derived) to specialized expert sub-networks, while also allowing interaction through shared experts. The decoder \( D_{MoST} \) processes the input sequence to produce output hidden states: \( \mathbf{H}_{output} = D_{MoST}(\mathbf{H}_{input}) \).
MoST is capable of generating both text and audio outputs. Text generation is handled by a standard language model head \( P_{text} \) applied to \( \mathbf{H}_{output} \), predicting the probability distribution over the vocabulary: \( P(\hat{\mathbf{T}} | \mathbf{H}_{input}) = \text{softmax}(P_{text}(\mathbf{H}_{output})) \). For audio generation, MoST employs a dedicated audio decoder \( G_{audio} \), specifically a HifiGAN vocoder \cite{kong2020hifigan}, conditioned on intermediate representations derived from \( \mathbf{H}_{output} \) (e.g., predicted HuBERT tokens) and potentially speaker embeddings \( \mathbf{s} \), generating the output waveform \( \hat{\mathbf{A}} = G_{audio}(\mathbf{H}_{output}, \mathbf{s}) \). This dual-output capability allows MoST to perform a wide range of speech-text tasks, including speech recognition, text-to-speech synthesis, and speech-to-speech translation, within a single model.
Figure \ref{fig:most_overview} (to be added) provides a schematic overview of the MoST architecture. Subsequent sections will elaborate on the audio processing components (Section \ref{sec:audio_encoder}) and the MAMoE mechanism (Section \ref{sec:mamoe}).
